Georgetown graduates have found success in a wide variety of fields, and have served at the heads of diverse institutions both in the public and private sector. Immediately after graduation, about 54C61% of undergraduates enter the workforce, while others go on to additional education.[213] Georgetown graduates have been recipients of 23 Rhodes Scholarships,[214] 21 Marshall Scholarships,[215] 26 Truman Scholarships,[216] and 14 Mitchell Scholarships.[217] Georgetown is also one of the top-ten yearly producers of Peace Corps volunteers as of 2010,[218] with 35 active and 866 total volunteers since 1961.[219] Georgetown alumni have a median starting salary of $55,000 with a median mid-career salary of $110,000.[213] NNDB, the Notable Names Database, lists 364 notable alumni as of 2013.[220]<br><br>

Eight former heads of state are alumni. Former President of the United States Bill Clinton is a 1968 graduate of the School of Foreign Service, and other former world leaders include Laura Chinchilla of Costa Rica,[221] Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo of the Philippines,[222] Saad Hariri of Lebanon,[223] and Alfredo Cristiani of El Salvador. Two SFS graduates are also currently elected presidents, Dalia Grybauskaite of Lithuania, who completed a six-month program in 1992,[224] and Zeljko Komsic, one of the tripartite Presidents of Bosnia and Herzegovina.[225] Six alumni serve in the United States Senate, and thirteen in the House of Representatives. Current congressional alumni include Dick Durbin, Senate majority whip, and Steny Hoyer, House minority whip.[226] Governor Pat Quinn of Illinois graduated from the SFS in 1971 while Governor Terry McAuliffe of Virginia received his J.D. from the Law Center in 1984.[227][228] On the U.S. Supreme Court, alumni include current Associate Justice Antonin Scalia and former Chief Justice Edward Douglass White.[220] Members of the current Obama Administration cabinet include Treasury Secretary Jack Lew who graduated from the law school in 1983 and Defense Secretary Chuck Hagel who was a faculty member at the School of Foreign Service from 2009 through 2013.<br><br>

King Felipe VI of Spain, King Abdullah II of Jordan, Prince Guillaume of Luxembourg, Prince Turki bin Faisal Al Saud of the Saudi Arabia royal family, and Prince Philippos of Greece and Denmark are among the royals who attended Georgetown.[229] Besides numerous members of the senior diplomatic corps, graduates have also headed military organizations on both the domestic and international level, such as former Secretary of Defense Robert Gates and former National Security Advisor General James L. Jones.[230] Notable alumni in business include Patricia Russo, former Alcatel-Lucent CEO, William J. Doyle of the Potash Corporation of Saskatchewan, and Ted Leonsis, owner of the Washington Capitals, Wizards, and Mystics franchises and former America Online executive.[231][232] Leonsis is among four other undergraduate alumni who own professional sports teams, making Georgetown the most popular undergraduate university for major North American sports franchise owners.[233] Actor Bradley Cooper, People Magazine's Sexiest Man Alive 2011, is also a graduate of Georgetown and its English program.[234]<br><br>


Alpha Phi Omega (ΑΦΩ) (commonly known as APO,[4] but also A-Phi-O[5] and A-Phi-Q[6]) is the largest collegiate fraternity in the United States, with chapters at over 350 campuses, an active membership of over 25,000 students, and over 400,000 alumni members. There are also 250 chapters in the Philippines and one in Australia.<br><br>

Alpha Phi Omega is a National co-ed service fraternity organized to provide community service, leadership development, and social opportunities for college students. Chapters range in size from approximately 10-20 active members to over 200 active members, independent of each college's size[citation needed].<br><br>

The purpose of the fraternity is "to assemble college students in a National Service Fraternity in the fellowship of principles derived from the Scout Oath and Scout Law of the Boy Scouts of America; to develop Leadership, to promote Friendship, and to provide Service to humanity; and to further the freedom that is our national, educational, and intellectual heritage."[7] Unlike many other fraternities, APO's primary focus is to provide volunteer service within four areas: service to the community, service to the campus, service to the fraternity, and service to the nation.
<br><br>
Being primarily a service organization, the fraternity restricts its chapters from maintaining fraternity houses to serve as residences for their members. This also encourages members of social fraternities and sororities that have houses to join APO as well.<br><br>

截至2011年，乔治城大学在全华盛顿地区三个校区中共雇佣了1291名全职及882名兼职教职人员[3]，此外，在卡塔尔分校中还有其他教职员[52]。教职员中包括不少杰出学者和知名政界及商界领袖，性别比例以男性占主导，约占总人数的三分之二[53]。在政治上，乔治城大学的教职员倾向于支持自由派候选人，而他们的捐资倾向与美国其他大学的教职人员一致。在乔治城大学教职员中，有超过平均水平比例的人在近年的美国大选中支持奥巴马[54][55]。
