	<b><a name="T25">The Evolution of SFS</a> </b><br>
	<hr><br>
	
The School of Foreign Service was founded in 1919 as a direct response to the involvement of the United States in the First World War. "Having entered upon the stage of world politics and world commerce, we assume world-wide obligations. Our viewpoint can never be the same again," wrote Edmund A. Walsh, S.J., the School’s first dean. SFS predates the U.S. Foreign Service by six years, and has been a leader in international affairs from the beginning. SFS celebrates its hundredth anniversary in 2019. Deans of SFS are listed in Appendix I.<br><br>

Through the Cold War and beyond into the new global challenges of the 21st century, Georgetown continued to strengthen its core undergraduate and graduate degrees in foreign service, and founded major regional studies centers and more specialized MA programs to better meet its core missions. Today SFS offers one undergraduate and eight graduate-level masters programs, each considered a leader in its field.<br><br>

- Bachelor of Science in Foreign Service<br><br>
- Master of Science in Foreign Service<br><br>
- M.A. in Global Human Development<br><br>
- M.A. in Security Studies<br><br>
- M.A. in Arab Studies<br><br>
- M.A. in Asian Studies<br><br>
- M.A. in Eurasian, Russian and East European Studies<br><br>
- M.A. in German and European Studies<br><br>
- M.A. in Latin American Studies<br><br>
In the past two decades, SFS has substantially expanded the range and depth of academic study and teaching to encompass all of the main areas of global interactions and policy challenges. The seven undergraduate majors in the School today provide training in the central dynamics of international economics, politics, culture, and science and technology. At the masters level, outstanding interdisciplinary degree programs cover all of the key regions, from Latin America to the Arab world, as well as functional areas such as security, international development, and international affairs. These curricular developments have been matched by the creation of research centers that provide a platform for vibrant engagement across the campus and far beyond Georgetown's gates.<br><br>
The expansion of the breadth of knowledge generated by the SFS community has occurred alongside a significant increase in the academic quality of Georgetown faculty and the scholarly reputation of the School. Faculty across SFS are internationally recognized as leading academic researchers. Expectations for hiring and tenuring of faculty have risen over time, parallel to the steady climb in the rankings of Georgetown’s international affairs programs.<br><br>
