In 2005, the University established the School of Foreign Service in Qatar (SFS-Q). The program has evolved and thrived in the decade since. The dean of SFS-Q currently reports jointly to the dean of SFS and to the University’s provost. The SFS-Q deans are listed in Appendix I.<br><br>
There are almost 50 faculty teaching on the Doha campus in Fall 2014, including six who are faculty at Georgetown in Washington (five based in the College and one based in SFS); the target of three Washington-based faculty serving in Doha each year has generally been met. The other SFS-Q faculty are recruited from around the world. Their disciplines include anthropology, Arabic, economics, French, history, philosophy, politics and international relations, religious studies and world literature. <br><br>

In light of Georgetown’s expanding offerings and with the encouragement of the leadership of the Qatar Foundation, general academic operations in Qatar eventually will become “Georgetown in Qatar” (just as the other institutions there are known by their institutions’ names, such as Northwestern in Qatar, Carnegie Mellon Qatar, and so on). SFS will still likely have the largest programs, but other programs will have the opportunity to flourish there as well. The new dean of SFS will be expected to take a substantial interest in the Doha campus, in order to continue the process of integrating the Doha programs into the life of SFS in Washington. The University’s 10-year contract with the Qatar Foundation is currently in the process of renewal; that process should be completed early in 2015.
