	<b><a name="T26">Current Strengths and Challenges</a> </b><br>
	<hr><br>
	
At this critical moment, President John J. DeGioia and Provost Robert Groves bring an exceptionally strong conviction that the School is central to Georgetown University’s future. Just as the University is in a dynamic period of reexamination, SFS has the opportunity to reflect on its accomplishments and its future so as to sustain its extraordinary leadership in the field of international affairs, to ensure that SFS faculty, students and alumni continue to be leaders in a very dynamic world, and to create a new constellation of partners.<br><br>
The core strengths of SFS today include the following:<br><br>
- The explicit integration of a truly global perspective, the rigorous analysis of functional issues, and an in-depth knowledge of regions and cultures, which endows the School with a unique comparative advantage;<br><br>
- An interdisciplinary curriculum (undergraduate and graduate) delivered by an interdisciplinary faculty;<br><br>
- An emphasis on foreign language acquisition and on analytical skills such as statistics and econometrics;<br><br>


- The twin values of research and teaching excellence;<br><br>
- The positive impulses that emanate from a confident and capable tradition of faculty governance;<br><br>
- The cooperative relationship that has characterized relations between faculty and administration over the years. The breadth of SFS encourages innovation within and among strong and dynamic individual centers, programs and institutes. These units offer degrees and certificates as well as supporting research, and they are the basis for the proven ability of SFS to respond energetically and flexibly to the challenges and opportunities of a changing world. Programs, centers and institutes are listed in Appendix II.<br><br>
Relationship of SFS to Other Schools/Units at Georgetown<br><br>
SFS has extensive relationships with other Schools at Georgetown. Many SFS faculty have joint appointments in Georgetown College, where most arts and sciences departments are located. Among other advantages, this provides access for those faculty to Ph.D. students. There are dual MA/PhD programs with many College departments, as well as dual MA programs with the McDonough School of Business, the Law Center, and the new McCourt School of Public Policy.<br><br>
