Resources<br><br>
The annual budget of SFS is about $55 million. These funds come primarily from tuition, from the proceeds of various endowments (currently totaling about $171 million), and from gifts and grants.<br><br>
The dean will have a substantial fundraising responsibility. Working within the framework of the University’s current capital campaign (described below), and perhaps within an SFS centennial campaign as well, the dean will collaborate with excellent development staff to attract essential financial resources. Fundraising priorities are all directed toward creating the conditions for excellence and success of faculty and students. The dean will likely devote about 30 percent of his or her time to development activities.<br><br>
The Dean’s Responsibilities and Opportunities<br><br>
During this dynamic period for the University, the new SFS dean will participate in making critical decisions that will shape the School’s future. The dean will have the following primary responsibilities and leadership opportunities:<br><br>
- Leadership and vision: The new dean will have the opportunity to lead the School and to energize its community at this critical moment of reflection and celebration, working with the faculty to sustain the approaches that have made great success possible, to address existing and anticipated challenges, and to chart new goals that will take SFS confidently into its second century.<br><br>
- Continued support for collaboration: Collaboration across units of the University is fundamental to SFS, as described above. At the same time, faculty recognize that there are exciting opportunities both to deepen existing collaborations and to build new bridges to other units at Georgetown. For example, initiatives currently underway within SFS in areas like environmental policy and climate change, public health, and cyber-security could lead to promising collaboration across the University. The support of a new dean in realizing these possibilities will be essential.<br><br>
-Program enhancements: Enhancing educational programs, building on recent external program reviews and other assessments; addressing critical program issues, including for example the broader national debate about the continuing relevance of area studies from both an academic perspective and the perspective of graduates’ potential employers.<br><br>
- Engagement with the Qatar campus: Supporting engagement of SFS Washington faculty in the Qatar campus, and collaborating with other deans to facilitate the evolution of SFS-Qatar to a campus with a broader focus.<br><br>

Professional Qualifications and Personal Characteristics<br><br>
The ideal candidate will have many of the following professional qualifications and personal characteristics:
- University experience: An advanced degree and scholarly accomplishments that earn the respect of the academic community; substantial understanding of scholarly research across a wide range of fields; familiarity with and ability to work effectively in the culture of higher education, including the expectations of shared governance. As noted above, the dean’s appointment will reflect the nature of his or her academic experience. - Experience as a practitioner in international affairs: Significant stature and recognition as a leader in global issues; extensive and high-level experience in the international policy arena (either in the public sector, in business, or in the NGO world), with the ability to draw upon that experience to build the engagement of SFS students and faculty beyond the campus.<br><br>
- Management experience: Substantial relevant experience in the management of complex organizations to manage budgets; select, support, develop, and supervise/direct staff and related personnel; and form effective partnerships with faculty and administrators across the University. - Commitment to quality: A record of recruiting and developing both people and programs of the highest quality.<br><br>
- Strategic vision: The ability to engage others in deliberation about the future of SFS; the capacity to bring people together across disciplines and programs in pursuit of continuing growth and improvement.<br><br>
- Engagement with students: Eagerness to engage with students and to promote their academic and professional development. - Fund raising: Ability to provide stewardship for philanthropic contributions by building strong relationships of mutual trust and respect with existing donors, including partnership with the Board of Visitors; eagerness to build resources by engaging new donors.<br><br>
- Collaborative abilities: Ability to work effectively across all of Georgetown’s academic units, and externally as well, to forge new partnerships. - Personal qualities: Commitment to Georgetown’s values, strong interpersonal skills and inclination to teamwork; an inclusive approach to individuals and organizations.<br><br>

